  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">5. How we use Cookies</h2>
  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">5.1 What Are Cookies?</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">A cookie is a small text file stored in your browser when you visit a website. It is sent back to the originating server on each subsequent visit, 
    allowing the site to recognise your browser and maintain basic functionality.</p>
  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">5.2 Cookies This Website Uses</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">This Website uses the following cookies:</p>
  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">- Rails 8 default Session Cookie</h4>
  <p>Purpose: in combination with the CSRF Token Cookie , it prrotects against forged requests (CSRF).  
    Also, temporarily carries one-time notification messages (flash messages) such as success or error alerts. Contains no personal information.</p>
  <p>Type: Functional / Strictly Necessary</p>
  <p>Duration: Expires when you close your browser</p>
  <p class="mb-4">Set by: Ruby on Rails (server-side framework)</p>
  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">- CSRF Token Cookie</h4>
  <p>Purpose: Protects form submissions against cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks — a standard web security measure</p>
  <p>Type: Functional / Strictly Necessary</p>
  <p>Duration: Expires when you close your browser</p>
  <p class="mb-4">Set by: Ruby on Rails</p>
  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">5.3 Managing Cookies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">You can control or delete cookies through your browser settings. Please note that disabling cookies 
    may affect the functionality of the contact form and other features of the Website. </p>
